Architecture plan for the 25-issue storefront implementation

Module structure and file organization

- Use a Next.js App Router project with TypeScript as the application shell.
- Keep route entry points under `src/app`:
  - `src/app/layout.tsx` for global metadata, fonts, shared shell, and cart header.
  - `src/app/page.tsx` for the storefront catalog entry.
  - `src/app/products/[slug]/page.tsx` for product detail pages.
  - `src/app/cart/page.tsx` for cart review.
  - `src/app/checkout/page.tsx` and `src/app/orders/[orderNumber]/page.tsx` for guest checkout and confirmation.
  - `src/app/admin/**` for authenticated product and order management.
  - `src/app/robots.ts` and `src/app/sitemap.ts` for SEO baseline.
- Put shared UI in `src/components`:
  - `src/components/layout` for header, navigation, cart badge, and page shell.
  - `src/components/catalog` for product cards, filters, category navigation, price display, and image treatment.
  - `src/components/cart` for cart line items, quantity controls, totals, and empty states.
  - `src/components/checkout` for guest checkout fields, validation messages, and order summary.
  - `src/components/admin` for admin forms, tables, upload controls, and order review panels.
- Put server-side application code in `src/lib`:
  - `src/lib/db.ts` for the Prisma client singleton.
  - `src/lib/catalog.ts` for product/category queries.
  - `src/lib/cart.ts` for session-backed cart read/write helpers.
  - `src/lib/orders.ts` for order creation and order lookup.
  - `src/lib/auth.ts` for admin auth/session helpers.
  - `src/lib/email.ts` for admin order notifications.
  - `src/lib/validation.ts` for shared Zod schemas.
  - `src/lib/format.ts` for currency, dates, and display helpers.
- Put server actions close to their domain:
  - `src/app/cart/actions.ts` for add/update/remove cart actions.
  - `src/app/checkout/actions.ts` for order submission.
  - `src/app/admin/products/actions.ts` for product CRUD and image upload coordination.
  - `src/app/admin/orders/actions.ts` for order status/review changes if needed.
- Put Prisma files under `prisma`:
  - `prisma/schema.prisma` for Product, Category, Cart, CartItem, Order, OrderItem, AdminUser/session-related models.
  - `prisma/seed.ts` for sample electronics catalog data.
- Put static assets under `public`, with product uploads using a later issue-specific storage decision. Local development can begin with `public/uploads`; production should use platform-compatible persistent object storage if available.
- Keep shared TypeScript types small and generated where possible:
  - Prefer Prisma-generated types for database records.
  - Add explicit view models in `src/lib/types.ts` only when UI shape differs from raw Prisma models.
  - Keep form input types inferred from Zod schemas.

Issue dependencies

- #1 is the base scaffold for all later work.
- #2 depends on #1 and provides the visual token foundation used by catalog, cart, checkout, admin, and final identity work.
- #3 depends on #1 and unlocks all persistent models and seed work.
- #4 depends on #1 and can run early once routing exists.
- #5 depends on #3 and defines Product/Category.
- #6 depends on #5 and provides development/test catalog data.
- #7 depends on #2, #5, and #6 for catalog listing and category filtering.
- #8 depends on #5, #6, and #7 patterns for product detail routing.
- #9 depends on #3 and introduces cart/session persistence.
- #10 depends on #9 and product queries from #5.
- #11 depends on #10 and shared layout from #1/#2.
- #12 depends on #3 and establishes order persistence.
- #13 depends on #11 and #12 for checkout UI and summary.
- #14 depends on #10, #12, and #13 for order creation from cart state.
- #15 depends on #14 for confirmation lookup and display.
- #16 depends on #14 and order data from #12.
- #17 depends on #1/#3 and gates admin routes before admin CRUD/review work.
- #18 depends on #5, #17, and validation helpers.
- #19 depends on #18 and final storage policy.
- #20 depends on #12, #14, and #17.
- #21 depends on #2 and the main storefront pages from #7/#8/#11/#13/#15.
- #22 depends on the user-facing flows being mostly complete.
- #23 depends on catalog, cart, checkout, and confirmation issues #7-#15.
- #24 depends on the major user/admin surfaces existing.
- #25 depends on the full app shape, environment variables, build scripts, migrations, and runtime assumptions being known.

Key design decisions

- Build as a server-first Next.js App Router app. Use React Server Components for catalog/product/order reads, server actions for mutations, and client components only for interactive controls that need browser state.
- Use Prisma with PostgreSQL as the source of truth. Keep migrations explicit and seed data deterministic so issue sessions can reset and verify behavior quickly.
- Use session persistence for guest carts via an HTTP-only cookie containing an opaque cart/session id. Store cart lines in PostgreSQL so cart state survives reloads without user accounts.
- Avoid introducing user accounts for shoppers. Admin authentication is separate and should be scoped to `/admin`.
- Use Zod for all form/server-action validation and reuse schemas between server actions and form components where practical.
- Treat money as integer cents in the database and format at the UI boundary.
- Use slugs for product/category URLs and keep ids internal.
- Use Tailwind tokens through CSS variables so later colorful identity work can adjust the system without rewriting components.
- Keep SEO metadata route-specific: global defaults in layout, product/category metadata from database records, and sitemap generated from persisted slugs.
- Make email delivery a replaceable adapter in `src/lib/email.ts`, configured by environment variables, so local development can log messages while production can use SMTP or a provider.
- Favor focused Playwright end-to-end coverage for the core shopping flow once checkout is complete, plus unit-level validation coverage only where domain logic becomes non-trivial.
